5|$|In October 1997, Brown {{took control}} of the United Kingdom's {{membership}} of the European <b>single</b> <b>currency</b> issue by announcing the Treasury would set five economic tests to ascertain whether the economic case had been made. In June 2003 the Treasury indicated the tests had not been passed.|$|E
5|$|The {{most obvious}} benefit of {{adopting}} a <b>single</b> <b>currency</b> {{is to remove}} the cost of exchanging currency, theoretically allowing businesses and individuals to consummate previously unprofitable trades. For consumers, banks in the eurozone must charge the same for intra-member cross-border transactions as purely domestic transactions for electronic payments (e.g., credit cards, debit cards and cash machine withdrawals).|$|E
